Let \(X\sim\text{Gamma}(1,\,\beta)\). So the pdf of \(X\) is
\[
f_X(x)=\beta e^{-\beta x},\quad x&gt;0.
\]

Find the cdf \(F_X(x)=P(X\leq x)\);
Find the inverse cdf \(F_X^{-1}(y)\), \(y\in(0,\,1)\);
Use your inverse cdf formula to compute the median of \(X\). It will be a function of \(\beta\);
Fix \(\beta = 2\). Use the qgamma function to compute the median of \(X\), and verify that you get the same number as you get when you use your formula from part c.

Problem 1
Say you have an unfamiliar coin on hand which may or may not be fair. So this coin lands on heads with some unknown probability \(p\), which is not necessarily equal to 1/2. Nevertheless, you want to somehow use this coin to generate the outcome of the flip of a fair coin. Consider the following algorithm for doing this:

Flip the coin;
Flip the coin again;
If both flips land on heads or if both flips land on tails, start over from Step (i);
If the two flips are different, let the result of the last flip be the result of the experiment.

Then:

Show that if you generate flips using this algorithm, the result is equally likely to be either heads or tails.
Here is another possible algorithm: flip the coin until the last two flips are different, and let the result be the outcome of the final flip. Are heads and tails equally likely using this procedure?

